Python Lists and Boolean Concepts
Comprehensive Teaching Notes for Examination and MCQ Preparation
Part 1: Python List Basics
1. A list is an ordered, mutable collection that allows duplicate values.
2. Lists are created using square brackets []. Example: numbers = [1, 2, 3].
3. Indexing starts from 0. First element is at index 0.
4. Negative indexing allows access from the end. Example: list[-1] gives last element.
5. Lists are mutable, meaning elements can be changed after creation.
6. The len() function returns the total number of elements in a list.
7. append() adds one element at the end of the list.
8. extend() adds multiple elements from another iterable.
9. insert(index, value) adds an element at a specific position.
10. remove(value) removes the first matching value, while pop(index) removes by index.
11. List slicing syntax: list[start:stop:step]. Stop index is excluded.
12. copy() creates a new list, while assignment creates a reference.
Part 2: Boolean Values
13. Boolean data type has only two values: True and False (case-sensitive).
14. bool() function converts values into True or False.
15. False values include: False, None, 0, empty string '', empty list [], empty dictionary {}.
16. Comparison operators: ==, !=, >, <, >=, <= return Boolean results.
17. Boolean values are commonly used in conditional statements like if, elif, else.
Part 3: Boolean Operations
18. Logical AND returns True only if both conditions are True.
19. Logical OR returns True if at least one condition is True.
20. Logical NOT reverses the Boolean value.
21. Operator precedence: not > and > or.
22. Python uses short-circuit evaluation in logical expressions.
